    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1945-09-07T09:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1945-09-07T09:00:00-05:00" n="492"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d492">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">740.00119 FEAC/9–745: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in the Soviet Union</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Harriman</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Moscow</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1945-09-07T17:00:00+03:00"
                            >September 7, 1945—5 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/> [Received September 7—1:28 p.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>3195. For the Acting Secretary. Molotov<note n="85" xml:id="d492fn1">Vyacheslav
                        Mikhailovich Molotov, People’s Commissar for Foreign Affairs of the Soviet
                        Union.</note> has written in reply to the note I sent him in accordance with
                    Dept’s 1881, August 21, 8 p.m.<note n="86" xml:id="d492fn2">See footnote 28,
                            <ref target="#pg_683">p. 683</ref>.</note> that the Soviet Govt agreed
                    to the proposal to establish a Far Eastern Advisory Commission.</p>
                <p>Clark Kerr<note n="87" xml:id="d492fn3">British Ambassador in the Soviet
                        Union.</note> asked Molotov personally yesterday for the Soviet reaction to
                    the British proposals regarding the functioning of the Control Council for
                    Japan. Molotov answered that the Soviet Govt had not formulated its views as yet
                    but that he expected the control <pb facs="0725" n="713" xml:id="pg_713"/> of
                    Japan to be one of the first matters considered by the meeting of the Foreign
                        Secretaries.<note n="88" xml:id="d492fn4">For first session of the Council
                        of Foreign Ministers at London, September 11–October 2, see <ref
                            target="frus1945v02#pg_99">vol. <hi rend="smallcaps">ii</hi>, pp.
                            99</ref> ff.</note>
                </p>
                <p>Repeated to London as 435 personal for Winant.<note n="89" xml:id="d492fn5">John
                        G. Winant, Ambassador in the United Kingdom.</note>
                </p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Harriman</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
